  "response": "Isaac Newton was not an atheist. He was deeply religious, although his religious views were somewhat unorthodox. He was a Christian, but he rejected the doctrine of the Trinity, which is a central tenet of many Christian denominations.\n\nHere's a more detailed breakdown:\n\n*   **Religious Belief:** Newton was a devout believer in God. He spent a significant amount of time studying the Bible and theological matters.\n*   **Rejection of the Trinity:** Newton privately rejected the traditional Christian doctrine of the Trinity (God as Father, Son, and Holy Spirit). He held what are often described as Arian or Socinian views, believing that Jesus Christ was subordinate to God the Father. He kept these views largely secret because they were considered heretical and could have had serious consequences for his career.\n*   **Emphasis on Reason and Empirical Evidence:** While deeply religious, Newton also believed in the importance of reason and empirical evidence. He saw science as a way to understand God's creation and to reveal God's laws. His scientific work was, in his mind, a form of religious inquiry.\n*   **Prophecy and Biblical Interpretation:** Newton dedicated a considerable amount of time to studying biblical prophecy and trying to decipher its meaning. He believed that the Bible contained hidden truths about the future.\n\nIn summary, Isaac Newton was a theist with unconventional Christian beliefs. He was not an atheist, but his rejection of the Trinity set him apart from orthodox Christianity.",
